'Tank Men' by Robert Kershaw is a really good book about the life of tank crews from WW1 to WW2 from the British, American, German and Russian accounts. The collection of these first hand accounts were quite chilling to read.

So I finally watched Fury, while it was a decent war movie, the action scenes were a bit outlandish for me which kept pulling me away from the experience. I do appreciate trying to depict warfare in its horror, certainly a heavier war film, reminded me of the book 'Tank Men'.

The thing about being in a project with other talented artists is having to remind my mind that my contribution is good and that they wanted it for that reason.

Right now I am getting real feelings of 'Did they make a mistake taking me on this project'

It is really difficult.

I was 16 in 2003, that was when I left school after my final exams. I lived my entire developing life ignorant of the support I was not allowed to have. Where the word "gay" was an insult hurled around by bullies. It certainly makes one think.

Section 28 was a law that prohibited the "promotion of homosexuality" by local authorities, including schools. Schools weren't allowed to teach anything about homosexuality and prevented support groups, this also implied homosexuals were dangerous to children.

You sometimes think that even as a UK queer person in their thirties that one had not been directed effected by a discriminatory law growing up but then one would read up things like Section 28, started by Margaret Thatcher's government and was only repealed in 2000-2003.

Rather than being used to reasure historic authenticity, they merely wanted to use her to reaffirm their notions. One email to her went "Kathy, we need to get a piece of evidence which proves that women gladiators had sharpened razor blades attached to their nipples." I mean, wow

I always knew that the film Gladiator wasn't accurate but I didn't know that it caused the historical consultant Kathleen Coleman to be so dismayed that she asked for herself to be removed from the credits of the film.
I think I can see the joke of Life of Brian's "What did the Romans ever did for us" in another way, making fun of the Hollywood epics of the past decades always depicting Romans as a villian.
Fun fact, an ancient roman chariot racer called Gaius Appuleius Diocles built a wealth of the equivalent of $15 billion. And you think modern sports stars are paid too much :p

I think the biggest warning when dealing with accounts of those depicting authoritarian themes (fictitious or otherwise) is when they use that theme as an avatar to express their own views (depicting killing 'sexual deviants' etc). You are then putting yourself as that regime.
Lets just say I noped the hell away fron that website after that.

I remember about 10 years ago playing a Web game called NationStates where you made decisions for you own nation of your imagination.

I tried their role-play forums for some fun fictitious diplomacy but when I went on there the number of people RPing fascist states unnerved me.

Now, people should never stop talking about history, even the dark parts. There should be stories, films and games but when I see people telling stories of a fascist regime (fictitious or otherwise) in a purely positive light with no reflection it makes me severely uncomfortable.

Combine this with romanticizing history can lead to troubling screwed views. Victoians romanticised medieval knights viewing the times like a Renaissance festival. I am troubled with individuals 'romanticizing' the rise of fascism.

While some see how things went too far, others will see it not going far enough. Others will say that things would have worked better if some individuals did things differently or never took the reigns of influence.
I love my history and I think it is important as we can learn a lot from it. Alas, even as much as I do believe in it, people will learn different lessons from the same events.
